# Databricks notebook source
# MAGIC %md
# MAGIC # Guidewire ODS — Three-Way DDL / Schema Drift Reconciliation
# MAGIC **Read Replica PROD (`core`, production truth) vs Read Replica TST (`core_tst`) vs CDA (`core_tst_std001`)**
# MAGIC
# MAGIC Scope: **schema/DDL only** — no row data is read. Data reconciliation is a
# MAGIC separate script by design (keeps this one fast, cheap, and safe to run
# MAGIC daily on serverless compute against ~2,000 tables).
# MAGIC
# MAGIC ### Why this is fast at 2K-table scale
# MAGIC Instead of calling `spark.table(...)` / `DESCRIBE` per table (thousands of
# MAGIC individual catalog lookups), this pulls the **entire column list for all
# MAGIC matching tables in one query per catalog** from
# MAGIC `<catalog>.information_schema.columns`. That's 3 SQL queries total for the
# MAGIC whole run, no matter whether you have 30 tables or 3,000. Everything after
# MAGIC that is pure in-memory Python dict comparison on the driver — no data
# MAGIC scanning, no shuffles, no RDD API, no cluster-specific config. This runs
# MAGIC cleanly on **serverless compute**.
# MAGIC
# MAGIC ### Three-way logic
# MAGIC - **PROD (`core`) is the source of truth.**
# MAGIC - **TST (`core_tst`) is also Read Replica** and is manually schema-controlled
# MAGIC   like PROD, so *any* difference from PROD is unexpected → treated as a
# MAGIC   **FAIL**.
# MAGIC - **CDA (`core_tst_std001`, `_cda` suffix)** is allowed to drift by design.
# MAGIC   Extra columns are a **WARN**; a column *missing* from CDA that exists in
# MAGIC   PROD, or a datatype conflict, is a **FAIL** (breaking, not just drift).

# COMMAND ----------
